00:02:23,136 --> 00:02:27,332
Kaplan operation and maintenance cost
incure for all stakeholders involved

53
00:02:27,532 --> 00:02:29,159
in faecal sludge management.

54
00:02:29,359 --> 00:02:32,668
This includes environmental
management authorities, 

55
00:02:32,868 --> 00:02:36,468
utilities, municipalities, private
companies,

56
00:02:36,668 --> 00:02:40,045
non-governmental or community
based organizations 

57
00:02:40,245 --> 00:02:42,312
and household level users. 

58
00:02:42,512 --> 00:02:45,609
These costs can be at very different
magnitudes and frequencies.

59
00:02:45,809 --> 00:02:48,019
So, whereas the capital cost
for the gulper

60
00:02:48,219 --> 00:02:50,386
is usually several hundred
US dollars

61
00:02:50,586 --> 00:02:53,141
depending on in which country
it is being manufactured.

62
00:02:53,354 --> 00:02:55,344
A vacuum truck, as shown
in this picture,

63
00:02:55,544 --> 00:02:58,199
may cost several thousand
or 10 thousand US dollars

64
00:02:58,399 --> 00:03:01,959
And a city scale treatment plant
as shown here in Kampala

65
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:04,013
several million dollars.

66
00:03:04,213 --> 00:03:06,991
So that faecal sludge management
service can be operated

67
00:03:07,191 --> 00:03:08,482
over a long period of time.

68
00:03:08,682 --> 00:03:12,992
Financial transfers need to balance
these costs of the different stakeholders.

69
00:03:13,192 --> 00:03:16,479
For example, our service provider
would commonly cover

70
00:03:16,679 --> 00:03:19,576
capital, and operational maintenance
cost.

71
00:03:19,776 --> 00:03:21,953
Through a service fee that
he receives from a household

72
00:03:22,165 --> 00:03:25,249
for the collection of faecal sludge
and transport to a treatment plant.

73
00:03:29,512 --> 00:03:32,237
If this service fee is the only
revenue stream

74
00:03:32,437 --> 00:03:33,994
and cannot cover its cost

75
00:03:34,194 --> 00:03:36,948
it will likely result in poor
performance of the service

76
00:03:37,148 --> 00:03:39,535
or it would go out of business.

77
00:03:39,735 --> 00:03:42,224
The number of financial transfers
in faecal sludge management

78
00:03:42,424 --> 00:03:45,088
strongly depends on the stakeholder
arrangement.

79
00:03:45,288 --> 00:03:48,143
This slide shows different
stakeholder arrangements

80
00:03:48,343 --> 00:03:50,112
for faecal sludge management.

81
00:03:50,312 --> 00:03:52,541
Each block represents
one stakeholder.

82
00:03:52,741 --> 00:03:56,100
In the first arrangement one
stakeholder manages the entire

83
00:03:56,300 --> 00:03:58,001
faecal sludge management
service chain

84
00:03:58,201 --> 00:04:01,201
and there are no financial transfers
between stakeholders.

85
00:04:01,401 --> 00:04:04,999
In contrast, other arrangements
such as the last one

86
00:04:05,199 --> 00:04:07,669
where four main, four stakeholders
managing

87
00:04:07,869 --> 00:04:09,522
the faecal sludge management
service chain

88
00:04:09,722 --> 00:04:11,230
includes more stakeholders

89
00:04:11,430 --> 00:04:15,071
and also potentially more financial
transfers between these stakeholders.

90
00:04:16,458 --> 00:04:19,480
This slide shows a common example
of institution arrangements

91
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:21,133
in faecal sludge management.

92
00:04:21,333 --> 00:04:24,586
That consists of a household,
a private company for faecal sludge

93
00:04:24,786 --> 00:04:26,237
collection and transport,

94
00:04:26,437 --> 00:04:28,406
a public utility
for faecal sludge treatment,

95
00:04:28,606 --> 00:04:31,778
And a farmer/industries that uses
faecal sludge treatment products.

96
00:04:31,978 --> 00:04:35,537
In a common financial flow model
for this institution arrangement

97
00:04:35,737 --> 00:04:38,625
the households pay a service fee

98
00:04:38,825 --> 00:04:40,449
to the private service provider

99
00:04:40,649 --> 00:04:43,826
for collection and transport
of faecal sludge treatment.

100
00:04:44,026 --> 00:04:47,771
At a treatment plant, the company
pays a discharge fee.

101
00:04:47,971 --> 00:04:51,546
This allows the service provider
to legally discharge sludge.

102
00:04:51,746 --> 00:04:55,073
This fee is paid in return
for transfer and responsibility

103
00:04:55,273 --> 00:04:57,576
managing the sludge
from the collection and transport

104
00:04:57,776 --> 00:05:00,334
service provider to treatment
service provider.

105
00:05:00,534 --> 00:05:04,537
The sale of treatment products
by the utility provides revenue

106
00:05:04,737 --> 00:05:05,944
for the utility.

107
00:05:06,144 --> 00:05:09,892
So in this example, the service fee,
the discharge fee, 

108
00:05:10,092 --> 00:05:12,592
and the revenue from the sales
of treatment products

109
00:05:12,792 --> 00:05:14,306
are financial transfers.

110
00:05:14,506 --> 00:05:17,198
The direction of the arrows
indicating which direction

111
00:05:17,398 --> 00:05:18,388
the money flows.

112
00:05:18,588 --> 00:05:21,384
This is why we also call this
financial flow models.

113
00:05:22,409 --> 00:05:26,499
Financial traces have an effect
up and down the service chain.

114
00:05:26,699 --> 00:05:29,150
For example, in a model
we just discussed

115
00:05:29,350 --> 00:05:32,350
one application could be when
the utility chain has a very high

116
00:05:32,550 --> 00:05:33,650
discharge fee.

117
00:05:33,850 --> 00:05:35,918
It will likely be passed on
to the household

118
00:05:36,118 --> 00:05:39,309
by a high service fee charge
by the collection and transport

119
00:05:39,509 --> 00:05:40,979
service provider.

120
00:05:41,179 --> 00:05:43,992
This could prohibit customers
being able to afford collection

121
00:05:44,192 --> 00:05:45,694
and transport services.

122
00:05:45,894 --> 00:05:47,979
Especially they're poor households.

123
00:05:48,179 --> 00:05:50,509
Another implication could be

124
00:05:50,709 --> 00:05:52,319
even when sludge is collected

125
00:05:52,519 --> 00:05:55,092
collection transport service
providers illegally dump sludge

126
00:05:55,292 --> 00:05:58,429
to avoid the high discharge fee
as shown here.

127
00:05:58,629 --> 00:06:03,158
In addition, as the public utility
operates without financial effort

128
00:06:03,358 --> 00:06:06,358
from the government authority
treatment could be less subject

129
00:06:06,558 --> 00:06:09,850
to regulations which could result
in a poor treatment performance

130
00:06:10,050 --> 00:06:12,780
or poor effluent quality.

131
00:06:13,193 --> 00:06:15,687
How could this financial flow model
be modified

132
00:06:15,887 --> 00:06:17,962
to reduce fees at the household level?

133
00:06:18,162 --> 00:06:20,052
Ensure that faecal sludge is safely
collected,

134
00:06:20,252 --> 00:06:23,510
reduce cost for the collection
transport service providers

135
00:06:23,710 --> 00:06:25,560
that it can make sustainable business.

136
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,689
